explanation:
For deciding whether any operations in parse_dauth_params are dead (their removal would not affect program behaviour) the next analyzer needs the concrete definitions/semantics of the following symbols:

- struct MHD_RqDAuth (definition): parse_dauth_params writes multiple fields of *pdauth (nonce, opaque, username, username_ext, realm, uri, qop_raw, cnonce, nc, userhash, algo3, qop). To determine whether those writes are observable (and thus not dead) you must know the exact layout and semantics of this structure and which fields are externally visible/used.

- struct MHD_RqDAuthParam (definition): local params and the locals userhash/algorithm are of this type; understanding what assignments to its .value and .quoted actually mean (and whether they have side effects) requires its definition.

- struct _MHD_cstr_w_len (definition): tk_names are arrays of this type and the code compares .len and .str; the exact member names/types confirm the matching logic and rule out e.g. side effects or alternate semantics that could make code necessary.

- _MHD_S_STR_W_LEN (macro expansion): used to initialise the token constants. The analyzer must know whether this macro does anything beyond producing simple static initialisers (no side effects) because a non-trivial expansion could make those definitions important for program behaviour.

- mhd_assert (macro / function): many mhd_assert() calls appear in the function. If mhd_assert has side effects (e.g. logging, abort) then those calls are observable and not dead; if it is compiled out to nothing they are dead. You need its definition to classify those statements.

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_bin_n_ (function): used in token name comparisons. If this function has side effects or non-standard semantics (e.g. modifies buffers, depends on global state) then the comparison code is not removable. Its behaviour (pure comparator or not) affects dead-code analysis of the matching loop.

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_quoted_s_bin_n (function) and MHD_str_equal_caseless_s_bin_n_ (function): used when post-processing userhash. Whether the call and the surrounding conditional/assignment are observable depends on these functions’ semantics (pure boolean tests or side-effecting). Also their return type/possible errors influence whether the userhash-related code is required.

- get_rq_dauth_algo (function definition): the return value is stored into pdauth->algo3. If get_rq_dauth_algo has side effects or its return influences external behaviour, then the call is not dead. If it is pure and unused elsewhere, that matters. You must inspect it to decide whether the call (and the data flow that prepares its argument) is removable.

- get_rq_dauth_qop (function definition): similarly, this is called with &pdauth->qop_raw and its result stored in pdauth->qop. Its side effects/semantics determine whether the call and preceding code that populates qop_raw are dead.

In short: to determine whether any assignment, loop iteration, call or assertion is dead you must know which writes are externally observable (via struct MHD_RqDAuth layout and usages) and whether called functions/macros (mhd_assert, comparison helpers, get_rq_dauth_*) have side effects. Those definitions are therefore required for a sound MISRA dead-code determination for parse_dauth_params.
